.section.benefits
  .container
    .row
      .col-xs-12.col-md-10.col-md-offset-1.intro
        %h2 The Benefits in detail

        %p.introText
          Writing Css code for a Sprite image can be quite a <strong>time consuming job as you always need to measure or look up each element's the x, y, width and height</strong>. And if elements change you need to go through your whole code to see where it needs to be updated.
          Wouldn't it be great if you could just forget about this and let it someone else handle it? <strong>Well, lucky you, that's where the Spriteowl comes in.</strong>

    .row
      .col-sm-4
        %h3.title
          What you get
        %p.content
          With Spriteowl you will not just get an <strong>optimized Png</strong> of your Photoshop sprite file, you also get a Stylesheet in which contains each <strong>layer's position (x/y) and dimension (width/height)</strong>.

      .col-sm-4
        %h3.title
          Preprocessors support
        %p.content
          When selecting one of the Preprocessors <strong>Less, Sass/Scss or Stylus</strong> you will get a Stylesheet as well as useful mixins from the <strong>#{link_to 'Cssowl\'s Sprite Package', 'http://cssowl.owl-stars.com/sprite.html', :target => '_blank'}</strong> with a lot of functions to position your sprite elements.

      .col-sm-4
        %h3.title
          Namespace support
        %p.content
          Spriteowl uses namespaces for bring your sprite elements into your Html, so you be no longer worry about position changes of your sprite elements in the original Psd file.



